If you don't want to use an external library, you can implement a simple Markdown parser yourself, but be warned that it's a complex task. Markdown allows for many edge cases and variations, making it challenging to write a fully compliant parser.

Here's a basic example without a library, supporting only a limited set of Markdown features:

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <sstream>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::stringstream html;
    std::string currentParagraph;

    for (char c : markdown) {
        if (c == '#' || c == ' ') {
            // Headings and spaces are ignored for simplicity
            continue;
        } else if (c == '*') {
            // Bold and Italic text
            if (markdown.find('*', markdown.find(c) + 1) != std::string::npos) {
                html << "<i>";
            } else {
                html << "<b>";
            }
        } else if (c == '[') {
            // Links
            size_t end = markdown.find(']');
            size_t start = markdown.find(',', end + 1);
            std::string linkText = markdown.substr(end + 1, start - end - 1);
            std::string linkUrl = markdown.substr(markdown.find('(', end) + 1, start - markdown.find('(', end) - 1);
            html << "<a href=\"" << linkUrl << "\">" << linkText << "</a>";
        } else if (c == '\n') {
            // New paragraphs
            if (!currentParagraph.empty()) {
                html << "<p>" << currentParagraph << "</p>";
                currentParagraph.clear();
            }
        } else {
            currentParagraph += c;
        }
    }
    if (!currentParagraph.empty()) {
        html << "<p>" << currentParagraph << "</p>";
    }

    return html.str();
}
```

Please note that this implementation is extremely basic and doesn't support many Markdown features. For a production-ready solution, consider using a well-maintained Markdown library.

